Show HN: A simple way to get a better job
text:
I‘m working on an education technology startup which allows users to do everything in terms of teaching and learning: any kind of content, private or public programs, paid or free, embed and etc.
But along with these features, I realised that this tool can help to get a better job in a simple way.
Every employer strives to have the best candidate and always looks for something special among nearly equal resumes (CV).
Let‘s imagine that your resume has a chapter Other activity - building my own academy to help younger professionals (and link to the profile).
Will it hook your employer? I guess so.
Another trick. The platform allows setting a password to access your content. So, if you urgently looking for a job you can create only titles, and chapters without content inside (no one will judge you for being in the process).
Public access to demo profile is here:

Pass: @sbtm2022

Ask HN: How to help aspiring business coaches?
text:
Hi, I'm an entrepreneur and I want to start a platform for aspiring business coaches. I want to get an opinion from experienced people on how in-demand this will be.

From my experience, I know that most coaches face at the beginning of their career that it's hard to gain credibility as a business consultant. Beyond that, they need support with defining a niche and the services they will provide. Last, but most important, is how to find their first clients and retain them.

For novice coaches, I want to launch a service that will:

- Introduce them to the coaching market - Help them identify a niche and services - Teach them how to sell their skills in a coaching format - Provide their first clients

What do you think about it? What are the existing competitors or analogues on the market? What are the chances for such a startup?

Thank you in advance for your opinion.

Ask HN: Alternatives to Mastodon?
text:
Curious to know as more people embrace Federation and Mastodon if there's any alternative platforms to look out for? I don't think Mastodon should necessarily hold a monopoly on what comes next. I'm experimenting with writing something from scratch (https://m3o.org) but am also interested to see what's out there that might be otherwise used.

The thing that Mastodon is highlighting is this move of communities to their own platforms that might be interconnected rather than just one giant centralised server governed by a corporation. I think from an end user perspective this isn't going to be vitally important but because mostly technologists drive bottom up trends it might become more prevalent. Email is always the thing to point to. So I don't think people will all necessarily run Mastodon servers but equally this may be the starting point for lots of new communication protocols.

title: Ask HN: What should I do with Blockfi holding my BTC collateral against my loan?
text:
I've got significant amount of money as BTC collateral at Blockfi.

I've heared that Blockfi maybe treats deposits chasing yields as loans, which I understand (and I understood the difference when I was taking out loan against my BTC collateral).

I'd like to repay my USD loan and get back my BTC collateral, as I made a mistake of trusting the company keeping funds separate.

I understand that I'll probably not see that money again, but my question is whether I should get a lawyer (and what kind of lawyer), or just wait to see what happens?
